<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,775,1377]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">
The detailed description of this crayfish strongly indicates that it is the common reef slipper or mitten lobster 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lund, 1793)" authorityName="Lund" authorityYear="1793" baseAuthorityName="Lund" baseAuthorityYear="1793" class="Malacostraca" family="Scyllaridae" genus="Parribacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antarcticus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">Parribacus antarcticus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Lund" box="[384,516,812,836]" firstAuthor="Lund" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" pagination="17 - 22" refId="ref11898" refString="Lund, N. T. (1793) Slaegten Scyllarus. Lagttagelser til insekternes Historie. I. Skrifter af naturhistoire Selskabet Kjobenhaven, 2 (2), 17 - 22, pl. 1." type="journal article" year="1793">
Lund, 
<number box="[459,516,812,836]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" value="1793.0">1793</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1825" box="[541,673,812,836]" class="Malacostraca" family="Scyllaridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Scyllaridae</taxonomicName>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Holthuis" box="[692,915,812,836]" firstAuthor="Holthuis" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" pagination="1" refId="ref11128" refString="Holthuis, L. B. (1985) A revision of the family Scyllaridae (Crustacea: Decapoda: Macrura). I. Subfamily Ibacinae. Zoologische Verhandelingen, 218, 1 - 130." type="journal article" year="1985">
Holthuis (
<number box="[805,866,812,836]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" value="1985.0">1985</number>
: 
<number box="[878,907,812,836]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" value="74.0">74</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
was the first to report 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Curtiss" authorityYear="1938" box="[1175,1328,812,836]" class="Malacostraca" family="Cancridae" genus="Cancer" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barffi">
<emphasis box="[1175,1328,812,836]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">Cancer barffi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lund" baseAuthorityYear="1793" box="[255,410,849,872]" class="Malacostraca" family="Scyllaridae" genus="Parribacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antarcticus">
<emphasis box="[255,410,849,872]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">P. antarcticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, although he did not explain why, and this synonymy has been followed by later workers (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Holthuis" box="[216,380,884,908]" firstAuthor="Holthuis" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 292" refId="ref11165" refString="Holthuis, L. B. (1991) Marine Lobsters of the World. FAO Species Catalogue, Vol. 13. FAO Fisheries Synopsis, Rome, 125 (13), 1 - 292." type="journal article" year="1991">
Holthuis 
<number box="[321,380,884,908]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" value="1991.0">1991</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Poupin" box="[394,541,884,908]" firstAuthor="Poupin" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" pagination="1" refId="ref12738" refString="Poupin, J. (1996) Crustacea Decapoda of French Polynesia (Astacidea, Palinuridea, Anomura, Brachyura). Atoll Research Bulletin, 442, 1 - 114." type="journal article" year="1996">
Poupin 
<number box="[482,541,884,908]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" value="1996.0">1996</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Chan" box="[554,680,884,908]" firstAuthor="Chan" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" refId="ref9668" refString="Chan, T. - Y. (1998) Lobsters. In: Carpenter, K. E. &amp; Niem, V. H. (Eds.), FAO species identification guide for fishery purposes. The living marine resources of the Western Central Pacific. Vol. 2. Cephalopods, crustaceans, holothurians and sharks. FAO, Rome, pp. 973 - 1043." type="book" year="1998">
Chan 
<number box="[621,680,884,908]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" value="1998.0">1998</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; Davie 
<number box="[769,830,884,908]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" value="2002.0">2002</number>
). Three other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dana" authorityYear="1852" box="[1111,1237,884,908]" class="Malacostraca" family="Scyllaridae" genus="Parribacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1111,1237,884,908]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">Parribacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
actually occur in 
<collectingCountry box="[151,349,919,943]" name="French Polynesia" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">French Polynesia</collectingCountry>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Forest, 1964" authorityName="Forest" authorityYear="1964" box="[360,635,919,944]" class="Malacostraca" family="Scyllaridae" genus="Parribacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="holthuisi">
<emphasis box="[360,485,920,944]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">P. holthuisi</emphasis>
Forest, 
<number box="[576,635,919,943]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" value="1964.0">1964</number>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Holthuis, 1960" authorityName="Holthuis" authorityYear="1960" box="[647,976,919,944]" class="Malacostraca" family="Scyllaridae" genus="Parribacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scarlatinus">
<emphasis box="[647,800,920,944]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">P. scarlatinus</emphasis>
Holthuis, 
<number box="[917,976,919,943]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" value="1960.0">1960</number>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Holthuis, 1967" authorityName="Holthuis" authorityYear="1967" box="[1035,1331,919,944]" class="Malacostraca" family="Scyllaridae" genus="Parribacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perlatus">
<emphasis box="[1035,1154,920,944]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">P. perlatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Holthuis" box="[1161,1331,919,943]" firstAuthor="Holthuis" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 28" refId="ref11024" refString="Holthuis, L. B. (1967) Stomatopoda I. Fam. Lysiosquillidae et Bathysquillidae. Crustaceorum Catalogus, 1, 1 - 28." type="journal article" year="1967">
Holthuis, 
<number box="[1272,1331,919,943]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" value="1967.0">1967</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but Curtiss’s (
<number box="[225,286,956,980]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" value="1938.0">1938</number>
: 
<number box="[300,400,956,980]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" value="163.5" valueMax="164.0" valueMin="163.0">163–164</number>
) observations that the “outer antennae have each four joints; the fourth, or final joint has eight spines at its tip, and some pale orange hairs ….. abdomen has bumps on the middle of the upper side of the second, third and fourth sections. The fourth section has its bump less noticeable, but those on the second and third sections stick out more ….. The body is variegated above, black and pale greenish; except for the fins at the end of the tail, which are pale orange; these fins are pale orange on their underside too, but the rest of the body is, on the under side, variegated with pale orange, pale greenish, and whitish”, indicate that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Curtiss" authorityYear="1938" box="[1075,1170,1136,1160]" class="Malacostraca" family="Cancridae" genus="Cancer" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barffi">
<emphasis box="[1075,1170,1136,1160]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">C. barffi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lund" baseAuthorityYear="1793" class="Malacostraca" family="Scyllaridae" genus="Parribacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antarcticus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">P. antarcticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The armature of the fourth antennal segment is important in separating the species, with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lund" baseAuthorityYear="1793" box="[1186,1338,1173,1196]" class="Malacostraca" family="Scyllaridae" genus="Parribacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antarcticus">
<emphasis box="[1186,1338,1173,1196]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">P. antarcticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Holthuis" authorityYear="1960" class="Malacostraca" family="Scyllaridae" genus="Parribacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scarlatinus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">P. scarlatinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Holthuis" authorityYear="1967" box="[285,406,1208,1232]" class="Malacostraca" family="Scyllaridae" genus="Parribacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perlatus">
<emphasis box="[285,406,1208,1232]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">P. perlatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
having six lateral teeth while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forest" authorityYear="1964" box="[753,881,1208,1232]" class="Malacostraca" family="Scyllaridae" genus="Parribacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="holthuisi">
<emphasis box="[753,881,1208,1232]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">P. holthuisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only has five such teeth (
<bibRefCitation author="Chan" box="[1177,1306,1208,1232]" firstAuthor="Chan" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" refId="ref9668" refString="Chan, T. - Y. (1998) Lobsters. In: Carpenter, K. E. &amp; Niem, V. H. (Eds.), FAO species identification guide for fishery purposes. The living marine resources of the Western Central Pacific. Vol. 2. Cephalopods, crustaceans, holothurians and sharks. FAO, Rome, pp. 973 - 1043." type="book" year="1998">
Chan 
<number box="[1246,1306,1208,1232]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" value="1998.0">1998</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). However, Curtiss obviously counted all the teeth around the antennal segment so this character is not helpful here. His observation of the median “bumps” on the abdomen is important as he observes that it is relatively high on the second and third somites. These median carinae are high in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lund" baseAuthorityYear="1793" box="[758,913,1317,1340]" class="Malacostraca" family="Scyllaridae" genus="Parribacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antarcticus">
<emphasis box="[758,913,1317,1340]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">P. antarcticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but low in the other species (
<bibRefCitation author="Chan" box="[1260,1391,1316,1340]" firstAuthor="Chan" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" refId="ref9668" refString="Chan, T. - Y. (1998) Lobsters. In: Carpenter, K. E. &amp; Niem, V. H. (Eds.), FAO species identification guide for fishery purposes. The living marine resources of the Western Central Pacific. Vol. 2. Cephalopods, crustaceans, holothurians and sharks. FAO, Rome, pp. 973 - 1043." type="book" year="1998">
Chan 
<number box="[1331,1391,1316,1340]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" value="1998.0">1998</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). In addition, the other species are red to orange in life, with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lund" baseAuthorityYear="1793" box="[783,935,1353,1376]" class="Malacostraca" family="Scyllaridae" genus="Parribacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antarcticus">
<emphasis box="[783,935,1353,1376]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">P. antarcticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
being the only green and black species.
</paragraph>
